Yeah, satisfaction I think is the most important thing.

65
00:02:33,939 --> 00:02:34,719
I think you set out,

66
00:02:34,740 --> 00:02:35,479
in a career,

67
00:02:35,580 --> 00:02:36,659
whatever industry it is,

68
00:02:36,680 --> 00:02:39,099
you set out to kind of do well

69
00:02:39,099 --> 00:02:40,099
and fulfil potential

70
00:02:40,099 --> 00:02:42,860
and to gain the respect of people

71
00:02:42,860 --> 00:02:44,759
that are in your industry

72
00:02:44,759 --> 00:02:46,400
but also outside if that's possible.

73
00:02:47,259 --> 00:02:50,080
And I remember when I signed for Man United,

74
00:02:50,180 --> 00:02:51,240
I think in my press conference,

75
00:02:51,300 --> 00:02:51,960
that's what I said.

76
00:02:52,240 --> 00:02:53,740
I said, if I can leave this club

77
00:02:54,360 --> 00:02:55,500
when I walk out the doors,

78
00:02:55,840 --> 00:02:57,680
as long as I've etched my name

79
00:02:57,680 --> 00:03:00,139
in the fabric of the club in a good way,

80
00:03:00,740 --> 00:03:02,520
which will mean having to win some stuff,

81
00:03:03,139 --> 00:03:04,500
then I would see that

82
00:03:04,500 --> 00:03:05,360
as being a success

83
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:07,900
and I'd like to think that I've probably done that.

84
00:03:08,199 --> 00:03:09,460
You're 23 years of age

85
00:03:09,460 --> 00:03:11,900
and you were named as captain of Leeds.

86
00:03:12,060 --> 00:03:12,960
You go on, as I said,

87
00:03:12,979 --> 00:03:13,659
to captain England,

88
00:03:13,840 --> 00:03:16,080
captain of the famous Manchester United.

89
00:03:16,219 --> 00:03:17,539
What were the traits, do you think,

90
00:03:17,560 --> 00:03:18,800
that people saw in you

91
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:21,340
to have you as a leader at such a young age?

92
00:03:21,460 --> 00:03:22,879
I think the fact that I could communicate

93
00:03:22,879 --> 00:03:25,139
would probably be one of my strongest points.

94
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:27,419
I think communication is something

95
00:03:27,419 --> 00:03:30,599
that's enabled me to have an afterlife in football as well

96
00:03:30,599 --> 00:03:32,759
in some of the businesses that I'm involved in.

97
00:03:32,759 --> 00:03:33,759
But on a football pitch

98
00:03:33,759 --> 00:03:34,139
and in a,

99
00:03:34,139 --> 00:03:36,360
in a football environment,

100
00:03:36,580 --> 00:03:38,460
I think communication and connecting,

101
00:03:39,740 --> 00:03:40,000
listen,

102
00:03:40,159 --> 00:03:41,280
a group of men,

103
00:03:41,340 --> 00:03:42,159
one of my teammates,

104
00:03:42,340 --> 00:03:44,800
likened it to being like 25 sharks in one room

105
00:03:44,800 --> 00:03:47,479
and being able to kind of connect those dots

106
00:03:47,479 --> 00:03:48,259
and connect those people

107
00:03:48,259 --> 00:03:49,180
from different backgrounds,

108
00:03:49,319 --> 00:03:49,960
different ages,

109
00:03:50,439 --> 00:03:53,680
really is important in cultivating a good environment

110
00:03:53,680 --> 00:03:56,120
that's conducive to winning trophies,

111
00:03:56,180 --> 00:03:57,439
not only winning a trophy,

112
00:03:57,539 --> 00:04:00,099
but winning on for a long period of time

113
00:04:00,099 --> 00:04:00,800
and consistently.

114
00:04:01,419 --> 00:04:02,319
And I think that's a key.

115
00:04:02,599 --> 00:04:03,000
Obviously,

116
00:04:03,159 --> 00:04:04,099
performance has to be,

117
00:04:04,139 --> 00:04:06,539
they have a high standard consistently as well

118
00:04:06,539 --> 00:04:08,560
on a day-to-day basis,

119
00:04:08,759 --> 00:04:11,120
setting them standards on a day-to-day

120
00:04:11,120 --> 00:04:12,719
was definitely key as well.

121
00:04:12,900 --> 00:04:16,800
So those areas there were probably the first things

122
00:04:16,800 --> 00:04:17,620
that probably stood out,

123
00:04:17,660 --> 00:04:18,540
I think, for any manager

124
00:04:18,540 --> 00:04:21,899
who's kind of contemplating giving me the armband

125
00:04:21,899 --> 00:04:22,819
and making me the captain.

126
00:04:23,560 --> 00:04:25,000
Listen, I think you'd notice

127
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:27,079
being somebody who's been involved in sport as well

128
00:04:27,079 --> 00:04:29,980
is that being able to talk to different types of people

129
00:04:29,980 --> 00:04:31,899
all in different ways is so key

130
00:04:31,899 --> 00:04:33,779
in making sure that you hit the right notes

131
00:04:33,779 --> 00:04:34,120
with people.

132
00:04:34,480 --> 00:04:37,120
To create a place where people feel like

133
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:38,379
they're okay to make mistakes,

134
00:04:38,660 --> 00:04:40,439
they'll get caught and held by other people

135
00:04:40,439 --> 00:04:41,100
in a change room,

136
00:04:41,160 --> 00:04:44,519
but also where they know there is a level of expectancy

137
00:04:44,519 --> 00:04:46,060
on a regular basis.

138
00:04:46,680 --> 00:04:48,639
It's an interesting description,

139
00:04:48,839 --> 00:04:51,519
25 sharks swimming around the one room.

140
00:04:51,699 --> 00:04:53,139
And it makes sense to me

141
00:04:53,139 --> 00:04:55,959
because effectively you're competing first and foremost

142
00:04:55,959 --> 00:04:57,639
for your own spot in a team,

143
00:04:58,120 --> 00:04:59,199
particularly at the high level

144
00:04:59,199 --> 00:05:00,759
of English Premier League football.

145
00:05:00,980 --> 00:05:02,620
And you've got incredibly talented people,

146
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:03,939
lots of big ego,

147
00:05:04,120 --> 00:05:06,319
lots of people who think they should play

148
00:05:06,319 --> 00:05:08,579
a role that maybe someone else has got.

149
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:10,439
And so it's not an easy mix, isn't it,

150
00:05:10,439 --> 00:05:11,920
to get team harmony,

151
00:05:11,920 --> 00:05:14,360
but you obviously had a way of being able

152
00:05:14,360 --> 00:05:15,279
to relate to everyone,

153
00:05:15,279 --> 00:05:17,680
even if they came from different backgrounds.

154
00:05:17,920 --> 00:05:19,660
Do you feel like that was a real skill of yours?

155
00:05:20,339 --> 00:05:21,160
Yeah, definitely.

156
00:05:21,300 --> 00:05:24,360
And I think that 25 sharks,

157
00:05:24,579 --> 00:05:26,439
the analogy is like you say,

158
00:05:26,779 --> 00:05:29,240
every single player in that squad

159
00:05:29,240 --> 00:05:32,060
of 26 players think they should be starting.

160
00:05:32,680 --> 00:05:34,079
There's 26 international players,

161
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:35,259
we play for their countries

162
00:05:35,259 --> 00:05:37,399
and there's probably 10,

163
00:05:37,800 --> 00:05:39,779
maybe 11 captains of their countries

164
00:05:39,779 --> 00:05:41,920
in our dressing room at any one time.

165
00:05:42,740 --> 00:05:44,240
So then to make sure that you create

166
00:05:44,240 --> 00:05:48,279
a harmonious environment is absolutely imperative

167
00:05:48,279 --> 00:05:50,540
because the moment you have one

168
00:05:50,540 --> 00:05:52,100
who's a little bit disjointed

169
00:05:52,100 --> 00:05:53,480
and steps out from the crowd

170
00:05:53,480 --> 00:05:54,639
and is allowed to do that,

171
00:05:55,199 --> 00:05:57,120
that becomes a bit of a cancerous person

172
00:05:57,660 --> 00:05:58,540
who then spreads

173
00:05:58,540 --> 00:06:00,120
and you can gain followers

174
00:06:00,899 --> 00:06:02,600
and people that stand alongside him

175
00:06:02,600 --> 00:06:04,060
because they're not in the team as well.

176
00:06:04,120 --> 00:06:06,120
And then that obviously then becomes a big problem

177
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:07,259
for the squad,

178
00:06:07,459 --> 00:06:08,079
the starting 11,

179
00:06:08,220 --> 00:06:09,079
the management staff.

180
00:06:09,339 --> 00:06:10,899
So that has to be managed.

181
00:06:11,019 --> 00:06:12,379
And I think the manager doesn't really,

182
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:13,920
that's weird because Felix Ferguson

183
00:06:13,920 --> 00:06:15,660
never really came into our changing room

184
00:06:15,660 --> 00:06:17,839
on a day-to-day basis at a training ground.

185
00:06:17,879 --> 00:06:20,620
He allowed not only the person wearing the armband,

186
00:06:20,720 --> 00:06:21,420
but like I said,

187
00:06:21,459 --> 00:06:22,939
there was other leaders in there as well

188
00:06:22,939 --> 00:06:26,120
to really manage the standards as well

189
00:06:26,120 --> 00:06:27,800
and punctuality, respect.

190
00:06:28,279 --> 00:06:29,899
And I think that's a huge thing as well

191
00:06:29,899 --> 00:06:31,180
is making sure that there's respect

192
00:06:31,180 --> 00:06:32,740
in the dressing room between teammates

193
00:06:32,740 --> 00:06:34,100
is a huge thing.

194
00:06:34,100 --> 00:06:35,899
And the players have to manage that.

195
00:06:36,439 --> 00:06:37,899
Like if someone steps out of line,

196
00:06:38,060 --> 00:06:39,519
they do something wrong

197
00:06:39,519 --> 00:06:41,379
or the intensity is not right on the day,

198
00:06:42,019 --> 00:06:43,660
there has to be the ability and the space

199
00:06:43,660 --> 00:06:45,439
for someone to challenge someone about that,

200
00:06:45,500 --> 00:06:47,439
but also to receive that in the right way.

201
00:06:47,720 --> 00:06:49,259
And if it isn't received in the right way,

202
00:06:49,319 --> 00:06:50,319
that person needs to be told.

203
00:06:50,759 --> 00:06:52,819
I'm fascinated that Sir Alex was someone

204
00:06:52,819 --> 00:06:55,319
that really left the locker room to the players.

205
00:06:55,439 --> 00:06:57,839
He didn't want to mingle and mix

206
00:06:57,839 --> 00:06:59,019
and socialise in there.

207
00:06:59,199 --> 00:07:00,199
That wasn't his go.

208
00:07:00,199 --> 00:07:03,199
It was something that he let the players go,

209
00:07:04,100 --> 00:07:04,939
and as you said,

210
00:07:05,220 --> 00:07:06,399
run that space themselves.

211
00:07:06,600 --> 00:07:07,800
Was that different to other managers?

212
00:07:08,319 --> 00:07:08,620
Yeah.

213
00:07:08,800 --> 00:07:10,079
I mean, some managers would come in,

214
00:07:10,100 --> 00:07:10,560
not a problem,

215
00:07:10,939 --> 00:07:11,800
and come in and see,

216
00:07:11,980 --> 00:07:14,620
put their head in there once a week.

217
00:07:14,860 --> 00:07:16,600
I don't think a lot of managers come in there a lot,

218
00:07:16,980 --> 00:07:20,060
but I was there 12, 13 years,

219
00:07:20,100 --> 00:07:22,220
and he probably came in three or four times max.

220
00:07:23,040 --> 00:07:24,399
And one of them was to say goodbye.

221
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:28,120
So I think the importance of,

222
00:07:28,199 --> 00:07:29,800
and I think that's one of his greatest attributes

223
00:07:29,800 --> 00:07:32,720
for Alex was that his ability to delegate

224
00:07:32,720 --> 00:07:33,939
and give other people,

225
00:07:34,100 --> 00:07:38,220
the space to kind of run their area of the football club,

226
00:07:38,279 --> 00:07:39,879
whether it be logistics,

227
00:07:40,160 --> 00:07:41,680
whether it be S&C,

228
00:07:41,860 --> 00:07:43,740
whether it be the physiotherapy,

229
00:07:43,920 --> 00:07:44,339
the doctor,

230
00:07:44,720 --> 00:07:46,420
them areas are run by those people.

231
00:07:46,980 --> 00:07:49,199
He was the overarching body that looked over things,

232
00:07:49,220 --> 00:07:50,980
and if it wasn't working or there was mistakes,

233
00:07:51,100 --> 00:07:52,959
and then you obviously go and see him,

234
00:07:53,079 --> 00:07:55,720
but he would leave people with the ability

235
00:07:55,720 --> 00:07:56,879
to go and do what you've got to do.

236
00:07:56,939 --> 00:07:57,379
You're here.

237
00:07:57,540 --> 00:07:59,240
I think that's a good thing he always used to talk about.

238
00:07:59,620 --> 00:08:01,100
You're here because you're good enough.

239
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:03,480
I've seen something in you that makes you good enough.

240
00:08:03,579 --> 00:08:04,079
Go and do that.

241
00:08:04,079 --> 00:08:06,600
That really gives you the confidence to go and perform.

242
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:08,800
Real, look, from an outsider looking in,

243
00:08:08,980 --> 00:08:11,639
and we all loved your era and one of the great eras in sport

244
00:08:11,639 --> 00:08:14,180
and the legend of Sir Alex Ferguson

245
00:08:14,180 --> 00:08:15,319
and what you guys achieved,

246
00:08:15,420 --> 00:08:18,220
but it looked like if you fell out with him, though,

247
00:08:18,860 --> 00:08:20,379
it was a pretty short conversation,

248
00:08:20,399 --> 00:08:21,860
and no matter how big you were,

249
00:08:21,939 --> 00:08:24,000
if you're David Beckham or Raya Ferdinand

250
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:24,779
or whatever it was,

251
00:08:24,819 --> 00:08:25,819
if you didn't quite fit,

252
00:08:26,259 --> 00:08:28,699
could he be quite brutal in that scenario as well?

253
00:08:28,879 --> 00:08:29,120
Yeah.

254
00:08:29,500 --> 00:08:31,399
Obviously, everyone's heard of the hairdryer

255
00:08:31,399 --> 00:08:34,059
where he unloads and gives it to you.

256
00:08:34,620 --> 00:08:35,200
But I'll be honest,

257
00:08:35,240 --> 00:08:37,220
I see a few people go back and forth with him.

258
00:08:37,299 --> 00:08:38,720
Beck's one, definitely.

259
00:08:39,600 --> 00:08:42,940
Roy, but I think it wasn't just like you had a problem,

260
00:08:43,179 --> 00:08:45,220
there was an issue and it was done and it was over

261
00:08:45,220 --> 00:08:46,259
and then you're gone.

262
00:08:46,379 --> 00:08:47,019
It wasn't like that.

263
00:08:47,059 --> 00:08:48,440
He was a fair person.

264
00:08:48,879 --> 00:08:50,379
But once he made a decision on you,

265
00:08:50,539 --> 00:08:51,639
that was it.

266
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:52,139
It was a definite.

267
00:08:52,860 --> 00:08:53,580
And to be fair,

268
00:08:53,679 --> 00:08:55,200
I had a few run-ins with him

269
00:08:55,200 --> 00:08:56,460
where I would challenge a decision

270
00:08:56,460 --> 00:08:58,580
or I wasn't happy about certain things.

271
00:08:59,539 --> 00:09:02,600
And I think if he believed it was coming from the right place,

272
